<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-447-183  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 447 183.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Sept 6 1990 v35 n18A p57(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Factory automation means jobs for US engineers; customer demandfor expertise and catchup game with Japanese spur hiring.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rooney, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The number of job openings for hardware and software engineers inthe factory automation market will continue to grow, though 'USspending on factory-automation control hardware, software, andservices' has dropped since 1985.andP;  Most US Fortune 500 companieshave implemented some degree of factory automation, led by thesemiconductor, automotive and aerospace industries.andP;  This mayrange from the use of robots and controllers to islands ofautomation and complete computer-integrated manufacturing systems.andO;The demand for factory-automation engineers is being driven by thefact that many manufacturers want factory-automation vendors tosupply the necessary engineers as well as train in-house engineersand pressure from Japanese competitors who use advancedfactory-automation technologies.andP;  Example employment opportunitiesand skills in demand are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TrendsOutlookEmployment OpportunityAutomationManufacturingIndustrial engineering.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>